Notes: Initially, WTD was recorded as -4.5cm while ALD was recorded as 29.5cm below water table. However, when corrected then to be relative to peat surface, that makes ALD shorter than the photo of the core, and above our recorded deep soil sampling depth.  | Notes (additional): Therefore, we have inferred that the ALD was mis-recorded initially and based on our interpretation of the photo, have here revised ALD to 27cm. See email stream from August 2011 with subject keywords "porewater samples" for full chain of discussion. For E-3, I just have "E-3-D, 24-27 cm" (actually 24-26 cm), with nothing from 22-24 cm.

Notes: negative water table depths denote surface water, depth to peat. No 3 cm temperatures- soil temps denote water temperature.  | Notes (additional): Forgot one set of 47 mm filter papers, so DOC samples were filtered at lab on July 12, ~16:00 from collected whole water samples. Eriophorum and sphagnum cores suffered a fair deal of compression, though difficult to quantify. Will likely need to use Wardenaar next time- will cause time constraint. Pore water sampling is quite time consumptive. Will not be able to 'suck' and core in the same day with only 2 ppl. If using Waardenaar. When collecting extra 1 cm section for bulk isotope/biogeochem samples, S and D was always 1 cm below microbial interval, M was always 1 cm above microbial interval. Bulk samples were refrigerated over night and split on the morning of the 13th. One should not use field styrofoam vial rack in -80 freezer if it has been a wet day. Instead one should dry the vials and transfer to new, dry cylinder rack. They freeze very tightly in place and make a mess of the foam when removing to tranfer into cryo-box.
